      <li>
       <img alt="Can we predict which molecules will set off the immune system? " class="ob1_img_device1" id="slide-number-3" longdesc="Electrostatics and statistical mechanics may have an answer that impacts autoimmune diseases.  ‘Toll-Like Receptors’ (TLR-9) in immune cells can bind to DNA from viruses as well as self-DNA from autoimmune patients and thereby initiate an immune response. A broad range of molecules can organize DNA into bundles with different structures. Due to statistical mechanics, only bundles with the right DNA spacing can drastically amplify immune response.  This discovery may lead to new therapeutic strategies for autoimmune diseases including lupus and psoriasis. 
" src="http://cbp.physics.ucla.edu/sites/default/files/banner/immune_system.jpg" title="Can we predict which molecules will set off the immune system? " typeof="foaf:Image"/>
       <div class="slider-caption">
        <h3>
         Can we predict which molecules will set off the immune system?
        </h3>
        <p>
         Electrostatics and statistical mechanics may have an answer that impacts autoimmune diseases.  ‘Toll-Like Receptors’ (TLR-9) in immune cells can bind to DNA from viruses as well as self-DNA from autoimmune patients and thereby initiate an immune response. A broad range of molecules can organize DNA into bundles with different structures. Due to statistical mechanics, only bundles with the right DNA spacing can drastically amplify immune response.  This discovery may lead to new therapeutic strategies for autoimmune diseases including lupus and psoriasis.
        </p>
       </div>
      </li>
      <li>
       <img alt="Walking bacteria" class="ob1_img_device1" id="slide-number-4" longdesc="We convert microscopy movies into searchable databases of bacterial behavior by using particle-tracking algorithms for quantitative analysis at fast time scales of all visible bacterial trajectories." src="http://cbp.physics.ucla.edu/sites/default/files/banner/walking_upright.jpg" title="Walking bacteria" typeof="foaf:Image"/>
       <div class="slider-caption">
        <h3>
         Walking bacteria
        </h3>
        <p>
         We convert microscopy movies into searchable databases of bacterial behavior by using particle-tracking algorithms for quantitative analysis at fast time scales of all visible bacterial trajectories.
        </p>
       </div>
      </li>
      <li>
       <img alt="Memory reorganization during sleep" class="ob1_img_device1" id="slide-number-5" longdesc="Memories are stored in both the neocortex and the hippocampus. Then, during sleep, the hippocampus, acting as a temporary storage system, is cleared for another day of learning, while the memories are retained in the neocortex, which provides permanent storage much like a computer hard disk." src="http://cbp.physics.ucla.edu/sites/default/files/banner/mouse_final.jpg" title="Memory reorganization during sleep" typeof="foaf:Image"/>
       <div class="slider-caption">
        <h3>
         Memory reorganization during sleep
        </h3>
        <p>
         Memories are stored in both the neocortex and the hippocampus. Then, during sleep, the hippocampus, acting as a temporary storage system, is cleared for another day of learning, while the memories are retained in the neocortex, which provides permanent storage much like a computer hard disk.
        </p>
       </div>
      </li>
      <li>
       <img alt="3D imaging of cells" class="ob1_img_device1" id="slide-number-6" longdesc="Yeast spores germinate when they encounter enriched nutrient conditions. The germination process includes four successive steps: a loss of refractility (darkening) of spores, protrusion of a new cell body, nuclear division, and septation." src="http://cbp.physics.ucla.edu/sites/default/files/banner/spores_final.jpg" title="3D imaging of cells" typeof="foaf:Image"/>
       <div class="slider-caption">
        <h3>
         3D imaging of cells
        </h3>
        <p>
         Yeast spores germinate when they encounter enriched nutrient conditions. The germination process includes four successive steps: a loss of refractility (darkening) of spores, protrusion of a new cell body, nuclear division, and septation.
        </p>
       </div>
      </li>
